    ],
    "search_text": "Ran Brosh Research Assistant Professor, Associate Director I have two roles: [1] as Faculty at ISG/Pathology I am leading the Dark Matter Project, a collaborative effort to use synthetic biology and genome writing to study the noncoding genome and its roles in health and disease. ACE2 humanized mouse models Big IN platform CRISPR activation rescue DHS element function mapping SARS CoV 2 susceptibility models SVA retrotransposon biology Sox2 locus control region TAF1 humanization X linked dystonia parkinsonism capture sequencing validation chromatin and transcriptome profiling landing pad based genome rewriting large DNA payload integration locus scale genome engineering mSwAP In iterative rewriting mammalian genome writing synthetic regulatory genomics",
    "lab_synopsis": "I have two roles: [1] as Faculty at ISG/Pathology I am leading the Dark Matter Project, a collaborative effort to use synthetic biology and genome writing to study the noncoding genome and its roles in health and disease. We develop method to build and deliver large DNA constructs to mammalian cells (primarily mouse embryonic stem cells) and apply them to generate mouse models for human diseases or in vitro cell models to study basic aspects of transcriptional regulation. [2] I'm the Associate Director of the Rodent Genetic Engineering Laboratory (RGEL), a core facility that generate transgenic mice by a variety of advanced methods.\n\nBuilds and applies genome writing platforms to rewrite large mammalian loci and model how regulatory DNA and transposable element insertions shape gene expression and disease phenotypes. Develops landing pad and large payload integration approaches such as Big IN and mSwAP In for iterative locus replacement in stem cells, enabling synthetic regulatory genomics studies including Sox2 locus control region dissection, ACE2 humanization for viral susceptibility models, and TAF1 humanization to test consequences of X linked dystonia parkinsonism associated SVA insertions. Supports end to end engineering workflows spanning design, assembly, validation, mouse model generation, and colony services.",
    "summary_short": "I have two roles: [1] as Faculty at ISG/Pathology I am leading the Dark Matter Project, a collaborative effort to use synthetic biology and genome writing to study the noncoding genome and its roles in health and disease.",
